  - q: "Why do German Shepherd puppies need special feeding?"
    a: "Three breed traits stack up. First, GSDs are a large, fast-growing breed prone to hip and elbow dysplasia, so growth must be kept steady and lean — overfeeding is genuinely harmful. Second, they have notoriously sensitive stomachs, and exocrine pancreatic insufficiency (EPI) is more common in German Shepherds than any other breed, so easily digestible, quality food matters enormously. Third, their deep chest makes them prone to bloat (GDV), a life-threatening emergency, so meal frequency and timing around exercise matter. Good feeding for a GSD pup balances all three."
  - q: "How often should I feed a German Shepherd puppy?"
    a: "More often than you'd feed an adult, and never one giant meal — this matters extra for a deep-chested, bloat-prone breed. Aim for roughly four meals a day to about 4 months, three to around 6 months, then two from there. Keep portions measured against your pup's expected adult weight (typically 30–40kg), feed from floor level in a calm setting, and avoid vigorous exercise for an hour or so before and after eating to reduce bloat (GDV) risk."
  - q: "Should a German Shepherd puppy eat large-breed puppy food?"
    a: "Ideally yes, or an all-life-stage food formulated with controlled calcium and energy. Large-breed puppy formulas deliberately limit calcium and calorie density to slow growth to a healthy rate, which protects developing hips and elbows. Energy-dense small-breed puppy foods can push a GSD pup to grow too fast. What matters most is that the food is complete for growth, has balanced (not excessive) calcium, is easy to digest, and that you portion it carefully to your pup's expected adult weight of around 30–40kg."
  - q: "My German Shepherd puppy has a sensitive stomach — what should I feed?"
    a: "Stick to a single, named animal protein, skip common triggers (grains, chicken, dairy and soy are the usual culprits for this breed), and choose a gently-prepared food — cold-pressed (Forthglade) or fresh, steam-cooked (Butternut Box, Years) is easier on the gut than high-heat extruded kibble. Introduce any new food slowly over 7–10 days. Persistent loose, greasy, pale stools, ravenous appetite with weight loss, or failure to thrive should prompt a vet visit — these can signal EPI, which German Shepherds are unusually prone to and which is very manageable once diagnosed."
  - q: "When should I switch my German Shepherd puppy to adult food?"
    a: "Later than a small breed. Because GSDs keep developing skeletally for longer, most should stay on a growth or all-life-stage food until around 12–18 months, sometimes to 24 months in larger working lines — switching too early can short-change late-stage development. The simplest route is an all-life-stage food like Forthglade, or a fresh brand that adjusts portions automatically, so there's no abrupt switch at all. When you do change, transition gradually over 7–10 days to protect that sensitive gut."
  - q: "Is grain-free food good for German Shepherd puppies?"
    a: "Grain-free suits many GSD puppies well, since grains are a common sensitivity trigger for the breed. The one nuance worth knowing: the dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM) heart concern raised in recent years has been linked to some grain-free recipes leaning heavily on peas, lentils and other pulses — so it's the legume load and recipe quality under scrutiny, not the absence of grain itself. Choosing a well-formulated brand matters more than the label. Years, for example, is both grain- and legume-free, which sidesteps the issue entirely."
